### Step 10: Dedicated Admin Quotes List — `src/app/[locale]/admin/quotes/page.tsx`

This is essentially a copy of the relevant part of `src/app/[locale]/admin/page.tsx` — the quotes list with filters and pagination — but as a dedicated route. The admin dashboard (`/admin`) can then either keep its list or link to `/admin/quotes` for the full list. The implementation mirrors the existing `admin/page.tsx` exactly (same `getAllQuotes` call, same `QuoteTable`, `QuoteFilters`, `Pagination` components). The only addition is a badge/indicator column for AI-generated quotes in the table, which requires a small change to `QuoteTable.tsx` to handle the `"ai-generated"` type label.

### Step 11: DB Insertion Script — `scripts/create-quote.ts`

```typescript
#!/usr/bin/env tsx
// Usage: npx tsx scripts/create-quote.ts --id <id> --file <path-to-md> --component <component-source>
// Called by the generation pipeline after files are written to disk.

import { createClient } from "@libsql/client";
import { nanoid } from "nanoid";
import { readFileSync } from "fs";
import matter from "gray-matter"; // add gray-matter as devDependency

async function main() {
  const args = Object.fromEntries(
    process.argv.slice(2).reduce<string[][]>((acc, arg, i, arr) => {
      if (arg.startsWith("--")) acc.push([arg.slice(2), arr[i + 1]]);
      return acc;
    }, [])
  );

  const mdPath = args.file;
  const raw = readFileSync(mdPath, "utf-8");
  const { data: frontmatter, content } = matter(raw);
  const id = args.id || nanoid(10);

  const db = createClient({
    url: process.env.DATABASE_URL || "file:local.db",
    authToken: process.env.DATABASE_AUTH_TOKEN,
  });

  const now = new Date().toISOString();

  await db.execute({
    sql: `INSERT INTO quotes (
            id, client_name, client_email, client_company, title,
            quote_type, currency, locale, valid_until,
            raw_content, generated_component,
            status, line_items, created_at, updated_at
          ) VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, 'ai-generated', ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, 'draft', '[]', ?, ?)`,
    args: [
      id,
      frontmatter.client_name, frontmatter.client_email,
      frontmatter.client_company || "",
      frontmatter.title,
      frontmatter.currency || "USD",
      frontmatter.locale || "en",
      frontmatter.valid_until || "",
      content,
      args.component || "",
      now, now,
    ],
  });

  console.log(`Quote created: ${id}`);
  console.log(`URL: /${frontmatter.locale || "en"}/quote/${id}`);
  process.exit(0);
}

main().catch(console.error);
```

Add `gray-matter` as a devDependency (`npm install --save-dev gray-matter`). It is a zero-dependency frontmatter parser.

Add a `package.json` script:
```json
"create-quote": "npx tsx scripts/create-quote.ts"
```

### Step 12: Claude Code Skill — `.claude/commands/generate-quote.md`

```markdown
---
description: Generate a bespoke AI quote from a markdown spec file
argument-hint: path/to/quote-spec.md
---

# Generate AI Quote

You are generating a bespoke client quote for PRAGMA, an AI consulting agency.

## Input
The argument is a path to a markdown file with this structure:
```
---
client_name: Acme Corp
client_email: cto@acme.com
client_company: Acme Corp
title: "AI-Powered Customer Support Automation"
currency: USD
locale: en
valid_until: "2026-06-30"
---

[Markdown body: full narrative of the engagement, problem, solution, deliverables, investment, next steps]
```

## Steps

1. **Read the input file** at the path provided as $ARGUMENTS.

2. **Extract the quote ID**: Generate a 10-character nanoid-style ID (alphanumeric, URL-safe) that will be used as both the DB id and the directory name. Example: `xK9mP2qR4s`.

3. **Generate `src/generated-quotes/Quote_[id]/QuoteContent.tsx`**:
   - A React Client Component (`"use client"` directive)
   - Props: `{ quote: Quote }` imported from `@/features/quotes/types`
   - Uses only Tailwind 4 utility classes (NO tailwind.config.ts — tokens are in globals.css as CSS variables: `pragma-bg`, `pragma-surface`, `pragma-border`, `pragma-accent`, `pragma-accent-2`, `pragma-accent-3`, `pragma-text`, `pragma-muted`, font-display: Space Grotesk)
   - Layout must be bespoke — not a copy of QuoteViewer. Design it to showcase the specific engagement.
   - Must NOT include the PRAGMA header/nav, locale switcher, PDF button, or Accept button — those are injected by AiQuoteShell.
   - Must export a named export: `export function QuoteContent({ quote }: { quote: Quote })`

4. **Generate `src/generated-quotes/Quote_[id]/QuotePDF.tsx`**:
   - Uses `@react-pdf/renderer` (Document, Page, Text, View, StyleSheet — no Canvas, no Image unless you have a URL)
   - Props: `{ quote: Quote }`
   - Named export: `export function QuotePDF({ quote }: { quote: Quote })`
   - White background, dark text — PDFs don't render CSS variables. Use hex values directly.
   - Mirror the structure of the web component but translated to PDF primitives.

5. **Update `src/generated-quotes/registry.ts`**:
   - Add the import lines for QuoteContent and QuotePDF
   - Add the entry to the `quoteRegistry` object
   - Preserve all existing entries — only append, never remove

6. **Insert the DB row** by running:
   ```
   npx tsx scripts/create-quote.ts --id [generated-id] --file [input-file-path]
   ```

7. **Output a summary**:
   - Quote ID
   - Client-facing URL: `/en/quote/[id]` (or `/es/quote/[id]` if locale is es)
   - Admin preview URL: `/en/admin/quotes/[id]`
   - Files created
   - Reminder: `git add src/generated-quotes/ && git commit` then deploy to Vercel

## Design Guidelines for QuoteContent

- Dark theme matching the PRAGMA design system
- Use `bg-pragma-bg`, `bg-pragma-surface`, `border-pragma-border`, `text-pragma-accent` etc.
- `font-display` class uses Space Grotesk — use it for headings
- Each engagement should feel hand-crafted: vary the section order, use callout boxes, highlight the most compelling number
- Animations: use `animate-fade-in` / `animate-slide-up` sparingly (defined in globals.css)
- The `quote` prop is passed through but you may choose which fields to surface — `raw_content` contains the full narrative, other Quote fields have the structured metadata
```

